<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="1127" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1127">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/2164</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Spring
                                Rice</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                            <gloss type="to">
                                <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                            </gloss>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-07">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 7, 1915</hi>.</date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 10</hi>.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Lansing</hi>: In connection with the
                            arguments which are now being advanced in various quarters with regard
                            to the propriety of the exportation of arms from the United States for
                            the use of the Allies, I have obtained some details, which may be of
                            interest, as to the exports of munitions of war from Germany to Great
                            Britain during the Boer war.</p>
                        <p>It appears that, after the Boer republics had been cut off from
                            communication with Europe by sea, 108 15-pounder quick-firing guns and
                            500 rounds of ammunition for each were bought from the firm of Erhardt
                            for the use of the British Army. Besides this order <pb facs="1045" n="787" xml:id="pg_787"/> large numbers of guns, rifles, and swords,
                            and also large quantities of shell, gunpowder, and small arms ammunition
                            were imported into England from Germany during the war.</p>
                        <p>Believe me [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>